Mr President , Commissioner Ferrero-Waldner , ladies and gentlemen , from the very outset , the European Union welcomed the creation of the United Nations Human Rights Council in 2006 , but has always stressed that it expected the Council to be an effective and credible body , which makes a real contribution to the protection of human rights at international level .
During previous sessions of the Human Rights Council , the European Union also attached the importance of substantive debates on human rights issues , as well as dialogue and close cooperation .
At the fourth ordinary session , the European Union and the African Group have managed to ensure that their resolution on Darfur is adopted by a consensus .
This resolution was the result of support efforts by the European Union , and this result reflects not only the Council mission , but also the level of responsibility that it is supposed to exercise .
The capacity of the Human Rights Council to fulfil its mission is indissociably linked to its composition .
I would like to remind you once again that the United Nations General Assembly expects nations of the Council to respect the highest human rights standards .
It has also invited all members of the United Nations to elect the Council alone of the nations with good results in the area of human rights .
Although this ideal is still a long way from being achieved , I would like to express the satisfaction of the European Union that Belarus &apos; s election in the Human Rights Council will be held successfully in May .
This success was due to the opposition of the European Union to Belarus &apos; s candidacy .
Although it is a minority in number , the European Union nevertheless plays a leading role in the Council , and has now been established as a major player .
Despite some encouraging developments , such as the adoption of an international Convention for the Protection of all persons against forced disappearances , more action needs to be taken to provide the Council on Human Rights for Practices and the labour instruments it needs to meet the expectations of the international community , and especially those of the European Union .
The European Union attaches absolute priority to the institutional establishment of the Council .
It therefore makes strenuous efforts to ensure that this process of building an institution is successfully finalised before the end of the first year .
The fifth session , which will take place in an imminent manner , will therefore be of crucial importance .
At this session , the Council will take its final decisions on the establishment of the institution and will determine , in the last analysis , its own efficiency and credibility over the next five years .
At present , the European Union is cooperating closely , in Geneva , with all participants in order to achieve a result which will enable the Human Rights Council to exercise its mission in full .
Within the framework of the contacts of the Union Presidency with the President and other delegations of the Human Rights Council , we are trying to establish an effective and credible Council within the United Nations system with a central role .
In this respect , the European Union wishes to emphasise the creation of an effective and universal periodic review process and the preservation of specific missions to certain subjects or countries .
The code of conduct provided for for for the special rapporteurs must not jeopardise their independence ; quite the contrary , it must guarantee independence and concentration on the obligations of the Member States with which the rapporteur cooperates .
Furthermore , we are pursuing the aim of establishing an appropriate procedure for selecting national representatives , which will ensure that they possess the required skills and ensure their independence .
We are aware of the difficulties involved in pursuing these objectives .
Let me assure you that we are not relaxing our efforts to achieve this .
On the other hand , the European Union still has a good hope that the Human Rights Council , with its regular intervalles throughout the year , its new improved set of instruments and its continuing commitment to dialogue with special rapporteurs and the High Commissioner for Human Rights , will gradually become a cornerstone of the UN Human Rights system .
It is now up to all members of the Human Rights Council to act responsibly and work to achieve these objectives .
Mr President , Mr Günter Gloser , ladies and gentlemen , since its foundation , the European Union , as you know , has been one of the main forces driving forces in the protection of human rights , and has therefore played an active role in pursuing the objectives of the Human Rights Council and ensuring that this new body represents a real improvement in the Commission &apos; s report on human rights .
The initial objectives were therefore to ensure that the Council &apos; s sessions deal with urgent issues concerning human rights , in the context of a very precise case , to improve coordination within the European Union , and to increase the efforts so-called &apos; atteindre &apos; , in other words , to raise the efforts to raise the European Union &apos; s external governments with human rights issues .
The real progress has been made in this respect , which allows us to have a coherent and credible attitude within the Human Rights Council and , on the other hand , to strengthen our cooperation with partners in other regions of the world , through bilateral meetings and within multilateral forums , and through a large campaign of awareness-raising awareness in many capitals in the world .
Of the priority tasks in the first year , therefore , the preservation of missions and mechanisms of the Human Rights Council within the framework of the process of examining and implementing the new system , known as universal periodic review , for the supervision of the human rights situation in all countries .
The compromise package presented yesterday only by the President of the Human Rights Council certainly goes in the right direction ; although it still needs to be improved , it is , however , very good from our point of view , a starting basis for the negotiations .
The fifth session of the Human Rights Council , which will be held next week , is therefore very special as the key to the future of this body .
This is another reason why I am particularly pleased that a delegation from the European Parliament to the session , within the context of the European Communities delegation .
What is the verdict on the performance of the Human Rights Council today ?
It is impossible to give a clear and clear answer , but , in my opinion , the Council should be a project in preparation , a kind of work ever finished , in some way .
Allow me to make a few brief comments .
The first sessions of the Council certainly were rather disappointing .
The old patters of behaviour have resurfaced .
Of course , we were already familiar with these schemes , since the Human Rights Commission .
The sessions on the Middle East , in particular , have really been wasted by the non-cooperative attitude of the same states which had convened them .
The result of this was draft unbalanced resolution which the European Union has not been able to support .
I would therefore like to make it very clear that , if confronting human rights issues may be necessary on the occasion , when fundamental rights are at stake , this is another matter where human rights are used as cover for continuing a conflict first and foremost political conflict .
Like the Council Presidency , however , we have also noted that the very good resolution devoted to Darfur , which has recently been adopted , has mitigated these unfavourable impressions .
I firmly believe that this is the most important resolution that the Council has adopted .
It has been coordinated closely with the African group , in very protracted negotiations , and has finally been adopted by consensus .
This was a remarkable outcome if we consider how sensitive the issue raised was , and the fact that the European Union can now be easily fighting to vote in the Human Rights Council .
The United Nations supervisory body of five independent rapporteurs , which had been set up by the resolution , will present its first report to the Council in the weeks that come , most likely next week .
And let us not forget that the International Court of Justice has recently indicted two Sudanese suspects .
In short , there are at least developments on this front in Darfur .
We very much hope that this will be an example , but will also set standards for the future work of the Human Rights Council .
Most recently , the interdialogues with the High Commissioner and the United Nations special rapporteur have proven to be a very useful development .
They have enabled us to approach the human rights situation in some countries - often in relation to more general human rights issues - in a very visible and procedural way that there is also much less confrontation .
Our next step , however , will be to find ways of ensuring that these dialogues can be followed by concrete progress on the ground .
As patients see rapid progress in the United Nations Human Rights Council , I would like to warn everyone of the judgments to be taken at this stage in relation to the Council .
All we can say at the moment is that there have been clear aspects and dark aspects .
We are convinced that the European Union will continue its efforts to take advantage of the encouraging developments that have occurred without doubt and feed , within the framework of intensive dialogue , with its partners in the United Nations , a UN Human Rights Council that is effective and , above all , a Council that is in the interests of the peoples concerned .
This is still the main international forum for the treatment of human rights , and we in the European Union have the responsibility of making an active use of it to consolidate our values , our ideals and our interests .
