Mr Mitchell , the Treaty defines stability as the main mandate .
The main mandate of the European Central Bank is to maintain stable prices .
Once this mandate or main objective has been achieved , or as it is achieved , the mandate is to ensure that monetary policy is coordinated with the rest of the objectives of economic policy .
This is something to which the ECB itself and the other European institutions must ensure .
What does the ECB mean by price stability ?
I believe that this has been defined very clearly in 2003 , if I am not mistaken .
This is meant by inflation below 2 % , but very close to 2 % in the medium term .
For all these years , from 1999 to date , this very just less than 2 % target has meant trying to maintain inflation at a low level .
Next year , if forecasts are correct , price stability could , for the first time , be interpreted as an attempt to maintain the 2 % without exceeding them , because we will probably live in a situation in which not only inflation in monthly terms , but perhaps even forecasts of inflation in the medium term will fall under the 2 % barre .
The mandate will remain the same , however .
The instruments used and methods for achieving the objectives will be different , of course , but the objective will remain the same .
The second area of activity or action of any central bank and , of course , of the European Central Bank , is to provide liquidity .
This is extremely important at present .
I believe that the ECB is doing what it has to do , but it does not make secret of the fact - it quite openly - that it provides liquidity this morning , but normally before closing the demagogic day , it receives liquidity of the financial institutions that have not used these liquidity for their credit operations .
This has now given rise to a debate : in recent days , newspapers publish statements by the Vice-President of the ECB , Mr Papademos , and other leaders that the bank and the way in which it should use the necessary instruments to ensure that this provision of liquidity is effective and not just a circulary operation that ends by a return to the money afternoon in which it was found in this morning .
I now come to the second question on the difference .
In some EU Member States outside the euro area , inflation is higher than in the vast majority of the euro area countries .
If you read the note that Eurostat has circulated on inflation at the end of November this morning , you will see that most European countries outside the euro area have a higher rate of inflation than the country with the highest rate of inflation within the euro area .
Therefore , there is more inflation outside , to a large extent , because there are countries outside this area that are going through a process of rapid convergence , where there is greater inflationary pressure due to a series of more married effects linked to the use of energy , to greater dependence on foreign energy sources whose price has increased , or to the &apos; Balassa-Samuelson &apos; effect in technical jargon .
In a sector comparison , inflation is clearly higher in the services sector .
Despite the very rapid fall of inflation in the last few months , you will see that inflation in the services sector has remained quite constant , to 2.6 % .
inflation in the food sector , food preparations and industrial products has fluctuated much more for the reasons I have outlined before my reply to Mr Medina Ortega .
However , the services sector has retained an inflation rate higher than the price stability objective , which is to remain below the 2 % barre .
However , its rate is still close to 2 % .
Subject : the Organisation for Economic governance of the European Union
Economic union , with its imperfections , and the full monetary union is accused of a notoriously asymmetry for what is regulatory pressure and its full binding character .
