Madam President , Mr Papastamkos is asking me about governance in the euro area .
I just just spoke of governance in the monetary pillar of the Economic and Monetary Union , the European Central Bank and the European system of central banks .
Very frankly , I think that it is working very well .
I believe that this is a success .
governance in the other pillar , the economic pillar of the Economic and Monetary Union , is working , but there is still a lot to be done .
The coordination of fiscal and budgetary policies is working , and I believe that , up to now , since the 2005 review , the Stability and Growth Pact and the budgetary coordination implicit in the implementation of the Pact have been working very well .
We are now subject to a very severe test , because , due to the economic slowdown and fiscal incentives , the more the packages intended to support the financial system , public finances are under extreme pressure and the Stability and Growth Pact must be implemented in a very difficult context .
It must be implemented with the flexibility it has , while maintaining and respecting the rules of the Pact , and this will be a major test .
There is also a second factor which is analysed in our report on the first ten years of the Economic and Monetary Union .
Beyond the coordination of our fiscal and budgetary policies , I believe that it is necessary to improve the coordination of our macroeconomic policies .
There are very significant macroeconomic imbalances in some countries , including Hungary and Latvia , which currently have enormous difficulties with their balance of payments and are asking for substantial financial assistance from us and from the Monetary Fund .
This indicates that there has been an accumulation of imbalances that we have not been able to correct in time through our coordination system .
These are countries which do not belong to the Economic and Monetary Union and which are at the third stage with the euro .
Even within the euro area , however , there are differences in current accounting deficits and developments in the unitary cost of labour .
I believe that they need more effective coordination than the one we have succeeded in providing up to now , despite the efforts of the Eurogroup in this regard .
I believe that the Eurogroup has done much better work since the Prime Minister of Luxembourg , Mr Juncker , took the Presidency in 2005 and has established a stable Presidency .
However , there is still a long way to go in terms of internal coordination of macroeconomic policies or certain structural reforms , which go beyond budgetary coordination , and there is clearly a lot to go to external coordination .
I believe that , as a currency , the euro is sufficiently important for us and the rest of the world not to allow us to fail to ensure that the interests , positions and priorities of the euro in the euro area countries are represented in fora and multilateral institutions in a coherent , systematic and integrated manner .
