Due to the underestimate of the risk of credit risk , rating agencies were one of the factors that trigger the global financial crisis .
Moreover , there is no genuine competition in the credit rating agencies sector .
This situation increases the risk of conflicts of interests and , by extension , lack of transparency and quality in terms of the allocation of notes to the various financial instruments .
The regulation giving rise to the creation of the European Securities and Markets Authority will enter into force on 1 January 2011 .
Its main prerogative will be to monitor the agencies of this kind .
The establishment of a monitoring and supervision mechanism for credit rating agencies at EU level is crucial .
I believe that this new authority must exercise its mandate as soon as its creation .
I would like to point out that the decision taken by the United States on the introduction of stricter control rules has paved the way for global harmonisation .
The European Union has already set out rules that will enter into force at the end of the year .
The rules for credit rating agencies that wish to operate in the European Union , and therefore obtain a licence , include , in particular , the obligation to register and comply with rules of transparency and &apos; specific &apos; conduct &apos; .
I do not believe that these rules are strict enough and I welcome the additional measures we are discussing in the Committee on Economic and Monetary Affairs .
These agencies currently have a great deal of power and may lead to a state and even a system ( by lowering the note of countries and causing a panic reaction to global markets ) in a crisis situation with one of their ratings .
Their work is important to ensure reliability and stability , but doubts remain about the rules and criteria based on their ratings .
Therefore , Mr Gauzès &apos; report , which proposes placing credit rating agencies under the supervision of the European Securities and Markets Authority , goes in the right direction .
